\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Bell Test with Continuous Variables
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Atul Singh Arora
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
University of Siegen, Germany
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
Indian Institute of Science Education & Research, Mohali, India
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Ali Asadian
\end_layout

\begin_layout Address
University of Siegen, Germany
\end_layout

\begin_layout PACS
Draft
\end_layout

\begin_layout Date
May-July 2015
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
We show the violation of the Bell inequality in a more classical setting
 than the usual quantum spin, viz.
 with continuous variables 
\begin_inset Formula $x,\, p$
\end_inset

.
 This is achieved using displacement operators, or equivalently modular
 momentum and position.
 Two possible experimental realizations of the scheme have also been delineated,
 one uses photons, while the other is based on electrons.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Bell inequality is a statement about the statistical outcomes of a certain
 class of experiments.
 The inequality was formulated by assuming the most general `local theory'.
 Any violation of the inequality would imply that local realism must be
 false.
 Quantum Mechanics predicts a violation which has been confirmed experimentally.
 The physical situation for which this violation is usually formulated,
 uses entangled spin states.
 Here we show that a violation can be achieved without having to use spins,
 which is a purely quantum phenomenon; measuring a particle's position is
 sufficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Violation of Bell Inequality
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
CHSH Inequality | prior art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here the violation of Bell's inequality for the typical spin case, is stated
 in a way that is easier to translate to the continuous variable case.
 We first state the Bell test in its modern form, known as the CHSH inequality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Suppose: There are two observers
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
that are often chosen to be sufficiently far away that their measurements
 don't influence each other
\end_layout

\end_inset

, Alice and Bob.
 There are two particles, which are allowed to interact initially and are
 then separated.
 Alice takes one, Bob takes the other.
 Alice can measure one of two properties of her particle, call them 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},\, a_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Similarly Bob can measure 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{1},\, b_{2}$
\end_inset

 of his particle.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Notatn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle a_{i}b_{j}\right\rangle =$
\end_inset

Average value obtained when Alice chooses to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}$
\end_inset

 and Bob chooses to measure 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Statemnt: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\left\langle a_{1}(b_{1}+b_{2})+a_{2}(b_{1}-b_{2})\right\rangle \right|\equiv\left|\left\langle C(a_{i},b_{i})\right\rangle \right|\le2$
\end_inset

 if (a) result of measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i},\, b_{i}$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\in\,[-1,1]$
\end_inset

, (b) local realism is assumed.
 This result will be referred to as the CHSH inequality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Quantum Mechanics predicts a violation of this in the following physical
 situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle \equiv\frac{\left|+-\right\rangle -\left|-+\right\rangle }{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

 where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\pm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 states are s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\sigma}_{x}\left|\pm\right\rangle =\pm\left|\pm\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Consider: (a) Two particles are described by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\psi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and (b) Alice measures 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 while Bob is allowed to choose between 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}'$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}'$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}'=\frac{-\hat{z}-\hat{x}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}'=\frac{\hat{z}-\hat{x}}{\sqrt{2}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Notatn: The Pauli matrices are referred to as 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x},\,\hat{y},\,\hat{z}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Result: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle C((\hat{x},\hat{z}),(\hat{x}',\hat{z}'))\right\rangle =2\sqrt{2}\nleq2$
\end_inset

, which is a violation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This value can be reproduced in a slightly modified situation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Modifictn: (i) Due to the symmetry in the setup, we expect the same results
 hold for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x},\,\hat{y}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}',\,\hat{y}'$
\end_inset

 and (ii) we demand that Alice and Bob can only measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 but are allowed to perform a local unitary before the measurement.
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Note that (ii) is equivalent to measuring along any direction.
 Details in the Apendix.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Explicitly then, consider: (a) Alice and Bob apply local unitaries 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{z}\theta/2}\otimes I$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $I\otimes e^{i\hat{z}\phi/2}$
\end_inset

 respectively and then both measure 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

.
 (b) Alice can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta\in\{0,\pi/2\}$
\end_inset

 and Bob can choose 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi\in\{\pi/4,\pi/4+\pi/2\}$
\end_inset

; see table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "mesSch1"

\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
These values are motivated by the 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/2$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, & 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi/4$
\end_inset

 between 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z'$
\end_inset

 in the conventional Bell case.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

