\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption

\begin_layout Plain Layout
`Corrected' Measurement Scheme 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "mesSch2"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle C\right\rangle =2\sqrt{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In conclusion, we have shown that, in the spin setting, the violation of
 the Bell inequality can be equivalently obtained by the measurement of
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}$
\end_inset

 after applying a rotation along 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 by the aforesaid angles.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Modular Variables and Displacement Operators | prior art
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The observables admissible in the CHSH inequality must 
\begin_inset Formula $\in[-1,1]$
\end_inset

.
 If we consider the 
\emph on
real
\emph default
 
\emph on
variable
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in(-\infty,\infty)$
\end_inset

, then one way of obtaining a bound variable is to use 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{mod}}\equiv p\mod h/L$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $h/L$
\end_inset

 has been introduced for dimensional reasons.
 This forces 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{mod}}\in[0,h/L)$
\end_inset

.
 If we further consider, say 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{\text{mod}}L/\hbar)$
\end_inset

, then we get precisely the bound needed for the CHSH inequality.
 We chose the constant factors so that for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{mod}}=h/L$
\end_inset

, the 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos$
\end_inset

 function also completes a period.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(p_{\text{mod}}L/\hbar)=\cos(pL/\hbar)=\frac{e^{ipL/\hbar}+e^{-ipL/\hbar}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Next, recall that in quantum mechanics, the momentum that's quantized, is
 one that generates infinitesimal translations.
 Formally, this means that 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(1-i\hat{p}\delta L/\hbar\right)\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x+\delta L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 If we want a finite translation, we can do the following procedure: 
\begin_inset Formula $\lim_{N\to\infty}\left(1-i\frac{\hat{p}}{\hbar}\frac{L}{N}\right)^{N}\left|x\right\rangle =e^{-i\hat{p}L/\hbar}\left|x\right\rangle =\left|x+L\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
 This operator is aptly called the displacement operator.
 We must add that 
\begin_inset Formula $e^{i\hat{p}a}e^{i\hat{x}b}=e^{i\hbar ab}e^{i\hat{x}b}e^{i\hat{p}a}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus for appropriate choices of 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

, the displacement operators can be made to commute or anti-commute.
 In the former case, it means one can simultaneously measure modular position
 and momentum (which is striking) and in the latter case, one can define
 pauli matrix like commutation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The idea was that the obvious generalization for obtaining an appropriate
 operator for the CHSH inequality is 
\begin_inset Formula $\cos(\hat{p}L/\hbar)=\frac{e^{i\hat{p}L/\hbar}+e^{-i\hat{p}L/\hbar}}{2}$
\end_inset

.
 While by construction this is bounded, the action of displacement operators
 will guide us in creating the appropriate states in the next sub section.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Violation in Continuous Variable State
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We start with constructing continuous variable kets
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
We emphasise that the kets we construct, will not be a countable superposition
 of eigenstates of 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 since these are highly idealized and strictly, not even a part of the Hilbert
 space.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 that satisfy the same orthogonality and mutual relations as 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle ,\left|1\right\rangle ,\left|+\right\rangle ,\left|-\right\rangle $
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|0\right\rangle ,\,\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 are s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}\left|0\right\rangle =\left|0\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{z}\left|1\right\rangle =-\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

 We then construct the relevant operators and finally evaluate 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle C\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 to show the violation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To construct the states, we start with some definitions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Forgt: 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x},\,\hat{y},\,\hat{z}$
\end_inset

 represent Pauli matrices
\end_layout

\begin_layout Labeling
\labelwidthstring a
Defn: 
\begin_inset Formula $L\equiv$
\end_inset

some length scale, 
\begin_inset Formula $N\equiv$
\end_inset

number of slits
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots/zeroOne.svg
	width 6cm
	BoundingBox 0bp 90bp 359bp 222bp
	clip

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x|\psi_{0}\right\rangle $
\end_inset

 (dashed) and 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x|\psi_{1}\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots/plus.svg
	width 6cm
	BoundingBox 0bp 90bp 359bp 222bp
	clip

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

(b) 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\langle x|\psi_{+}\right\rangle $
\end_inset


\begin_inset VSpace bigskip
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Graphics
	filename plots/minus.svg
	width 6cm
	BoundingBox 0bp 20bp 359bp 200bp
	clip

\end_inset


